#!/usr/bin/env ssc
---
name: v2-native-result-unregistered-field
description: v2 fieldAt crashes on a native (extern) function's case-class-shaped result whose class was never declared in this compile unit
backends: [int]
---

# v2 field access crashes on a native result whose case class isn't imported

Minimizes busi's `repo_git_mirror` v2-sweep failure. The pattern: call a
GLOBAL, extern-backed std function (`exec`, from std/process.ssc, bound by
the os-plugin) WITHOUT importing its declared return type (`ProcessResult`)
‚Äî busi's `core/repo_git_mirror.ssc` does exactly this (calls `exec(...)`
bare, never imports `ProcessResult`; the plugin bootstraps globally once
ANY extern-backed std function is used elsewhere in the file ‚Äî here,
`exists` from std/fs.ssc, matching git_mirror's own `readFile`/`mkdirs`
imports). Then dot into the result's fields (`r.exitCode`, `r.stdout`).

v1's interpreter resolves `.exitCode` DYNAMICALLY by name against the
native result's own field map ‚Äî it never needs to know `ProcessResult`'s
shape ahead of time, so this "just works" regardless of import.

v2 compiles named field access to a STATIC `fieldAt(recv, index, name)`
using a GLOBAL, receiver-blind field-name‚Üíindex registry built only from
`case class` declarations TEXTUALLY PRESENT in the compiled unit. Since
`ProcessResult` is never imported here, its shape is unregistered ‚Äî the
v1‚Üív2 bridge can't build a proper `DataV("ProcessResult", ‚Ä¶)` for the
native result and falls back to a raw/foreign representation. `fieldAt`'s
runtime fallback then calls `asData` on that non-`DataV` value and crashes:
`RuntimeException: expected Data, got ProcessResult(...)`.

This is a GENERAL v2 gap, not process-specific: any native/extern function
returning a case-class-shaped value whose class isn't ALSO imported in the
same compile unit will hit this. Repro:
`bin/ssc --v2 tests/conformance/v2-native-result-unregistered-field.ssc`
(v1 lanes below pin the correct, passing behavior).

Found 2026-07-09 minimizing busi's `repo_git_mirror` v2-sweep failure.

[exists](std/fs.ssc)

```scalascript
case class MyStep(label: String, exitCode: Int, stdout: String)

def run(label: String): MyStep =
  val r = exec("echo", List(label), 0)
  MyStep(label, r.exitCode, r.stdout)

val s = run("hi")
println(s.exitCode)
println(s.stdout.trim())
```
